## System Architecture

This is a full-stack application with a Vue 3 frontend and FastAPI backend, orchestrated by Nx.

```
Browser  -->  Vite (:4200)  -->  /api/*  -->  FastAPI (:8080)
```

- **`api/`**: FastAPI backend, managed by uv. Source code in `api/src/{{package_name}}/`.
- **`ui/`**: Vue 3 SPA, built with Vite. Proxies `/api` requests to the backend in development.
- **`nx.json`**: Nx orchestrates tasks across both projects.

See [`full-stack.md`](full-stack.md) for frontend conventions and backend patterns.
{% if hexagonal %}
### Backend layering (hexagonal)

The `api/` backend is structured as **hexagonal architecture** (ports & adapters), with boundaries enforced by [import-linter](https://import-linter.readthedocs.io/) (`uv run lint-imports`, run in pre-commit and CI).

| Layer | Package | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Domain | `{{package_name}}.domain` | Pure business logic and models. No HTTP, no I/O. May depend only on port protocols. |
| Ports | `{{package_name}}.ports` | `Protocol` interfaces, split `inbound` (driving) and `outbound` (driven). |
| Adapters | `{{package_name}}.adapters` | Concrete implementations: `inbound` (HTTP routes) and `outbound` (DB / clients / etc.). |
| Application | `{{package_name}}.application` | Config and the composition root (`application/app.py:create_app`) â€” the single place adapters are chosen and wired. |

**Dependency direction:** `adapters â†’ application â†’ ports â†’ domain`. A layer may import those below it, never above.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["adapters<br/>inbound.http"]
    APP["application<br/>composition root Â· config"]
    P["ports<br/>inbound Â· outbound"]
    D["domain<br/>check_health Â· HealthReport"]

    A --> APP
    APP --> P
    P --> D

    APP -. "exception: composition root wires adapters" .-> A
```

`{{package_name}}.app:create_app` (the uvicorn `--factory` entrypoint) is a thin shim that re-exports the composition root.

**Adding your first outbound port.** The scaffold ships layers-only (no example port), so the import-linter config starts minimal. When you add an outbound integration:

1. Define the `Protocol` in `ports/outbound/<name>.py`; have the domain import it as needed.
2. Implement it in `adapters/outbound/<name>/` â€” ship a real adapter **and** an in-memory fake (the fake doubles as a test double and a dependency-free local mode).
3. Wire the choice in the composition root (`application/app.py`).
4. Extend the import-linter config in `pyproject.toml`: if the domain imports the port, add `"{{package_name}}.domain.** -> {{package_name}}.ports.**"` to `ignore_imports`; once you have two or more outbound adapter families, add an `independence` contract over them.

